SmartAssembly (Redgate)', 'Provides protection against reverse engineering, tampering, and IP theft of software by modifying the source code (or an intermediate representation thereof) using techniques such as branch protection, control flow flattening, data transformations, variable obfuscation, constant and symbol hiding, function transformations, security in-lining, and white box cryptography. The resulting software, once compiled, is typically hardened against static and dynamic (run-time) analysis.This tool is used as an alternative to 4.1 Binary Protection Tool. ', 'Source code or intermediate representation of source code, obfuscation settings/parameters', 'Obfuscate code and data, inject white box crypto', 'Hardened source code and transformed data, ready for compilation', 'No hard interfaces; tool can be inserted into the build pipeline as an extra step', 'Future ETSI standard on external encodings for Advanced Encryption Standard (AES)', '', '', 'Irdeto', '', ''),
('3.2', '3. Code', '3.2 Code Analysis Tools', 'Fortify Static Code Analysis Tool (Micro Focus), Checkmarx Static Application Security Testing (Checkmarx),  Static Analysis Tool (Veracode), Coverity Static Analysis (Synopsis), AppScan (IBM), SonarQube, Clang Static Analyzer (freely available), TiCS', '<p>Code analysis tools analyse source code with the help of advanced compiler-construction techniques (e.g., data and control flow analysis) to detect potential low-level security bugs. Typical bugs include buffer/heap/integer overflows, code injection vulnerabilities (e.g., SQL injection, Cross-Site Scripting), cryptographic misuse, simple race conditions. Typically provides TQI, based on consolidation of various software quality metrics like test coverage, abstract interpretation, cyclomatic complexity, compiler warnings etc.<br></p>', 'Source code of the software to be analysed; rules to be checked against the source code (rule-set)', 'Automated static analysis of the source code against defined security rules', 'A list with all potential findings (low-level bugs), often a classification as to the severity of the finding, ', 'Integration with an IDE sometimes possible, in some cases online service allowing one to upload the source code', 'OWASP Top 10, SEI CERT coding guidelines, Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), ISO Standard 25000, ISO/IEC 25010.', '', '<ul><li>KPI-01 “Undetected documented vulnerabilities on devices” </li><li>\r\nKPI-02 “Undetected documented vulnerabilities in releases” </li><li> \r\nKPI-03 “Time to automated investigation” </li><li> \r\nKPI-05 “Human interactions from commit to secure deploy” </li><li>\r\nKPI-08 “Open source released toolkit(-document) components” </li><li>\r\nKPI-11 “Undetected license/legal violations”</li></ul>', 'Otaris, Diebold Nixdorf, Anywi, Almende', 'check status', ''),
('5.1', '5. Test', '5.1 Verification Testing Tools', 'IoT security verification standard (NVISO), IoT testing guide (NVISO), Tools to test/read out the configuration of an IoT application (NVISO), etc…', 'Assist security testers in their\r\nsecurity testing activities', 'An IoT application (code build) together with the physical embedded device.', 'Tools are used by the security tester to verify security requirements ', 'Pass/fail', 'Not relevant to the security verification standard or testing guide. The tools however, will interface with the IoT application through a certain interface (can really be anything depending on the application)', 'Security verification standard will be based on the common ground found between many existing IoT security requirement standards. For example, through teaming up with OWASP IoT. ', '', '<p>An IoT application (code build) together with the physical embedded device. Security assessments can be either:&nbsp;</p><p>- White box: the security tester is provided with all of the required information to perform the test. For example, accounts, source code, architecture design, etc…&nbsp;</p><p>- Black box: the security tester is provided only with the physical embedded device running the application.</p>', 'Nvisio', '', NULL),
('6.1', '6. Release', '6.1 Threat Checking Tools', 'Xray (JFrog), OWASP Dependency-Check (OWASP), CVE-check-tool (Clearlinux)', '<div>Threat checking tools generally operate on the release artefact repository and perform a composition analysis of the components that make up the release of a software application or system. The purpose of this is to identify publicly disclosed vulnerabilities contained within these components.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div>', 'Release artefacts, publicly known vulnerabilities (CVE database)', 'Analysis of composition of the release', 'Notifications of detected common vulnerabilities', ' No hard interfaces', ' ', '', '', '', '', NULL),
('7.1', '7. Deploy', '7.1 Identity & Security Provisioning Tools', '', 'Generates and assigns identities\r\nand associated security assets to IoT devices in a secure manner. This may\r\ninclude assets such is unique identifiers, X.509 certificates, symmetric keys,\r\npasswords, and associated metadata that is required for securely managing a\r\ndevice throughout its entire lifecycle.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nThe generation of security sensitive items is done in a trusted environment,\r\ntypically using a hardware security module (HSM). The provisioning of these\r\ndata can be done into silicon chips during a so-called personalisation process,\r\nin a manufacturing facility where the device is assembled, or online when the\r\ndevice is first connected to a network.', 'Number of identities to generate, optionally with unique identifiers', 'Secure generation of certificates, keys, passwords, etc and association of these assets with unique identities. Provisioning of these identities into chips or devices.', 'Certificates, keys, passwords, etc.', 'Configuration (types of assets required), number of identities required, optionally unique identifiers', '', '', '', 'Irdeto Werner, NXP ', ' ', NULL),
('7.2', '7. Deploy', '7.2 Secure Deployment Tools', 'Crownstone Update Framework (Almende)', 'Facilitate secure firmware updates for networks of IoT devices. Users are able to deliver new firmware to devices for which they are authorised, without risk of “bricking” i.e. getting the device stuck with incomplete code, and without risk of outsider tampering\r\n\r\n', 'Function calls & firmware payload', 'Secure transfer and install of firmware payload', 'none', 'Direct interfacing with firmware code; format and size requirements for payload', '', '', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Initial\r\nConcept</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The\r\nframework has two versions:</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:36.0pt;text-indent:-18.0pt;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo1;\r\ntab-stops:list 36.0pt\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\r\nmso-fareast-font-family:\"Times New Roman\"\">-<span style=\"font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \"Times New Roman\";\">       \r\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\">One\r\nis implemented on IoT devices, and handles the validation and reception of\r\nfirmware updates as well as the spreading to other IoT devices in its network.</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:36.0pt;text-indent:-18.0pt;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo1;\r\ntab-stops:list 36.0pt\"><!--[if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\r\nmso-fareast-font-family:\"Times New Roman\"\">-<span style=\"font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-stretch: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: \"Times New Roman\";\">       \r\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The\r\nother is implemented on mobile devices, edge devices and servers, and handles\r\nthe signing of firmware updates as well as transfer.</span><o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Users are\r\nassigned personal keys that are installed on their IoT devices, which ensure\r\nthat only they can authorise updates. Firmware updates without the right keys\r\nare rejected by the IoT devices. Updates may be directly issued from mobile or\r\nedge devices on scene, or first pushed/pulled from remote servers, as the\r\nframework should facilitate any number of hops before the transfer to the IoT\r\ndevices.</span><o:p></o:p></p>', 'Almende, AnyWi, ', 'Check almende for status', NULL),
('9.1', '9. Monitoring', '9.1 Threat Monitoring Tools', 'Darktrace, FireEye (Cisco), Vectra AI (Vectra), QRadar (IBM)', 'Threat monitoring tools typically monitor network traffic between endpoints on an IT or OT network in order to detect cyber-threats and latent vulnerabilities. These systems are configured to understand - or in some cases use AI to learn - what \'normal\' behaviour is, and then flag any deviations from this norm (anomalies). This can generally identify a wide range of threats, from malware to network intrusion.<br>', 'Network traffic, configured or learned understanding of ”normal” behavior', 'Analysis of the network traffic and flows', 'Notifications of detected anomalies', 'Network interface', 'Stride', '', '', '', 'check status', NULL),
('1.1', '1. Requirements, 2. Design, 3. Code, 5. Test', 'Requirements Management and Validation Tools', 'Jira (Atlassian), Jama Connect (Jama Software), Rational Doors (IBM), ReQtest', 'Provides full management of the life-cycle of requirements (also called epics, user stories, or features), including definition, modelling of dependencies, visualization, status tracking during design, coding, &amp; testing, and more.', 'User inputs relating to requirements', 'Evolution of definition of requirements and tracking of various statuses associated with requirements', 'Unambiguous requirements; reports detailing requirements coverage during design, coding, and testing', 'The tool may have interfaces with the development tools, test subsystem, documentation tools ', 'ANSI/IEEE Guide to Software Requirements STD 830-1984', '', '', '', 'Obsolete', NULL),
('9.2', '9. Monitoring', '9.2 Incident Reporting Tools', 'Nagios, Veeam, datadog, solarwinds, Famatech Advanced IP Scanner, Icinga, LibreNMS, Wireshark, Zabbix, Graylog', 'Monitoring IoT infrastructure\r\ncomponents', 'Network traffic, Log files, System events, rules', 'depends on the rules and used tool', 'Messages of harmful events, blocking of certain devices', 'depends on the tool', 'depends on the tool', '', '', '', 'Investigate further', NULL),
('6.2', '6. Release', '6.2 Dataflow Protection Test Tools', 'Wireshark, mitmproxy, OTALYZER (extension based on Wireshark and mitmproxy output)', '<p><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\">Automatically\r\nanalyzing traffic data (</span><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\">e.g</span><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\">, in </span><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\">pcap</span><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\">\r\nformat) w.r.t. </span><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\">dataflows</span><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\"> that violate privacy and security\r\nrequirements </span><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\">pcap</span><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\" century=\"\" gothic\";\"=\"\"> input with the help of a keyword\r\nsearch</span></p>', 'Key word list (e.g., add blocking lists/host files), pcap files,  mitmproxy files', 'Automatically analyzing pcap or mitmproxy files regarding key words to identify privacy violations (e.g., tracking), perfoming IP address look-ups and reverse DNS to identify servers', 'List of findings', 'pcap, mitmproxy files (traffic captures)', 'pcap format', '', '<p>Can be used in release Phase, Test and Monitoring)</p>', 'Otaris', 'API is under development for integration in the scratch pipeline (e.g. Jenkins, drone, Docker? or other)', ''),
('5.2', '5. Test', '5.2 Penetration Testing Tools', '- Tools that allow to intercept/alter communication of IoT specific communication protocols.- Tools that allow the extraction of certain configuration properties of certain embedded platforms- Tools that can interface with certain chips', 'Tools will allow a security testers to gain access to the required input required to\r\nuse the verification testing tools as defined in 5.1.', 'Embedded application and physical device', 'Depends on tool', 'Access to required input for 5.1', '', '', '', '', 'Almende Anywi Diebold Nixdorf and Xabier', 'Check progress', NULL),
('2.2', '2.Design 3.Code 4. Build', '2.2 SDK Blueprint', 'SDKs usually vendor and solution specific like NXP MCUXpresso SDK Builder ', '<p>The blueprint of the SDK is to\r\nreplicate the SCRATCh\r\ndevops\r\nenvironment with the vendor specific tools and (if possible) provide a vendor\r\nagnostic solution to incorporate the SCRATCh\r\ndevops\r\napproach</p>', 'SCRATCh devops processes and HW/ SW selection', 'Preparation of SDK to meet the process requirements and get a quick start from 1. requirements to 5. testing', 'A testable application either in a simulator or on hardware ', 'Interfaces to process and hardware components', '', '', '<p>A standard environment to implement secure element for development of new IoT devices</p>', 'NXP', '', NULL),
('3.3', '3. Code', '3.3 IDE / Text Editor', 'sonacube', '<div>Aid in the construction, formatting and maintenance of large amounts of code within a project. Enable automatic detection of bad coding practices.</div><div><br></div>', 'Code', 'Auto-completion; detection of errors and weaknesses', 'Formatted code', 'Code file formats', '', '', '', 'Otaris, Diebold Nixdorf, Anywi', 'check Code test and verification test static', NULL),
('1.0', '1. Requirements, 2. Design, 3. Code, 5. Test', 'Development & Test Best Practices; Security & Vulnerability Knowledge Base', '', '<p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt; font-family: Arial;\">Provides essential advice and\r\nstandards for Secure DevOps. Includes major established standards.</span></p>', 'Standards, methods, documents, Ontology', 'Searching and filtering', 'manually obtained, Important requirements and guidelines for a development process.', 'Only Human Interfacing', '', '', '<p>A quick reference to decide on basic Security requirements, testing and certification schemas.</p>', 'Franklin Cedric', '', NULL),
('8.2', '8. Operate ', '8.2 Deception Toolkits', 'DFKI, OSfuscate', '<p>The purpose of this tool is to impede the reconnaissance phase of an attacker. According to the Lockheed Martin Cyber Kill Chain, this phase is the first in a series of hostile activities. A directed manipulation of the hostile reconnaissance output therefore affects the entire process of hostile activity. Ideally, deception allows immediate impact on the prevention of an attack.<br></p>', 'Server side code, and binaries at link time (Code, Build)Running system (Operate, Monitor)', 'Insert protection and monitoring features in runtime binary (Code, Build)Provides threat monitoring information (Monitor)Prevents attacks on running systems (Operate)', 'Application with runtime protectionSystem with embedded monitoring capability (able to produce relevant telemetry) and the ability to prevent certain types of attacks', 'No hard interfaces; tool can be inserted into the build pipeline as an extra step', 'Lockheed Martin Cyber Kill Chain', '', '<p>We expect research progress in the three domains <b>IPv4 address randomization</b>,<b> TCP stack manipulation</b> and the <b>deception proxy</b>. Issues that emerged from our previous work are:</p><ul><li>How can traffic interruptions during an IP address randomization be bypassed?<br></li><li>How can users maintain an overview during the complicated process of randomization?<br></li><li>Is it possible that systems imitate the TCP signatures of an arbitrary operating system from a database and thus impersonate it during OS scans?</li><li>Does the TCP stack manipulation cause severe errors? If yes, how can we resolve them?<br></li><li>How can decoys be injected into application layer traffic?<br></li></ul>', 'DFKI', 'Tools in development', NULL),
('4.1', '4. Build', '4.1 Binary Obfuscation Tools', 'Application Protection™ (Arxan), Code Protection™ (WhiteCryption), Denuvo Anti-Tamper (Irdeto)', '<div>Provides protection against reverse engineering, tampering, and IP theft of software by modifying the binary code using techniques such as branch protection, control flow flattening, data transformations, variable obfuscation, constant and symbol hiding, function transformations, and white box cryptography. The resulting binary is typically hardened against static and dynamic (run-time) analysis.This tool is used as an alternative to 3.1 Source Code Protection Tool.</div><div><br></div>', 'Binary code, obfuscation settings/parameters', 'Obfuscate binary and data, inject white box crypto', 'Hardened binary code and transformed data', 'No hard interfaces; tool can be inserted into the build pipeline as an extra step', 'Future ETSI standard on external encodings for Advanced Encryption Standard (AES)', '', '', 'Irdeto', '', NULL),
('5.3', '5. Test', '5.3 Unit Test Prioritization Tools', 'Tselect, Xray, Jnan', 'Create a market ready test case\r\nselection and prioritization tool, which can be delivered as a library,\r\nindependent tool or a plugin, to optimize testing of embedded systems in a\r\ncontinuous integration environment.', 'Test Suite, Historic data, Requirements, Code Changes (e.g., .xml, .json)', 'Test case prioritization according to input data', 'Prioritized test cases', 'No hard interfaces. The tool can be inserted as a library, an independent tool or a plugin in the testing phase of the development cycle.', '', '', '<p>Generic tool customization for different platform and Implementation environments</p><p>Prioritization of test scenarios</p>', 'ULMA, Xabier', 'Ongoing', NULL),
('8.1', '3. Code, 4. Build, 8. Operate, 9. Monitor ', '8.1 Runtime Application Self Protection Tools', 'Rackspace, Travis CI, Puppet, Chef', 'Provides protection against\r\nrun-time attacks on applications by using information from runtime\r\ninstrumentation and by using technologies such as anti-debug, integrity\r\nverification, and secure loading. Tools in this category can operate in a\r\nmonitor-only mode, a protect-only mode, or both.', 'Server side code, and binaries at link time (Code, Build)Running system (Operate, Monitor)', 'Insert protection and monitoring features in runtime binary (Code, Build)Provides threat monitoring information (Monitor)Prevents attacks on running systems (Operate)', 'Application with runtime protectionSystem with embedded monitoring capability (able to produce relevant telemetry) and the ability to prevent certain types of attacks', 'No hard interfaces; tool can be inserted into the build pipeline as an extra step', 'STRIDE', '', '', '', 'check with Irdeto', NULL),
('6.0', '6. Release; 7. Deployment', '6.0 Release & Deployment Best Practices', '', '<p>Provides essential advice and\r\nstandards for Secure DevOps. Includes major established standards.</p>', 'none', 'Searching and filtering', 'manually obtained, Important requirements and guidelines for a development process.', 'Only Human Interfacing', '', '', '<p><br></p>', 'Franklin Cedric', '', NULL),
('8.0', '8. Operate; 9. Monitor', '8.0 Operational Best Practices', '', '<p>Provides essential advice and\r\nstandards for Secure DevOps. Includes major established standards.</p>', 'none', 'Searching and filtering', 'manually obtained, Important requirements and guidelines for a development process.', 'Only Human Interfacing', '', '', '<p><br></p>', ' ', '', NULL);

